725768f-a.text:
102nd Street (left foreground), at the S.W. corner of Corona Ave. (formerly Newton Ave.), showing the farmhouse of George I. Rapelye from 1852 to 1873. George I. Rapelye was born in Nova Scotia in 1787. His father returned to Newtown in 1792. George I. Was still living in 1882. The old number of this house was 60; it is now 9932 Corona Ave. The house was renovated in 1933, and opened to the public as the New
Cottage Inn in November 1933.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

this house belonged to one Reed in 1891.

726417f-a.text:
Corona Avenue, at the S.W. corner of 102nd Street, showing an old type frame house. Corona Avenue, here, was formerly known as Newtown Avenue, and 102nd Street as Mulberry Avenue.
P. L. Sperr  June 7, 1927

726420f-a.text:
Corona Avenue, north side, between 102nd and 104th Streets, showing the Geo. W.Burroughs house of 1852 to 1873. It was erected by John Burroughs who died in 1750. His sons John and Joseph inherited the farm. Joseph's son Thomas was the next owner. He married Sarah,daughter of George Wyckoff. His son was Geo. Wyckoff Burroughs and his daughter married Isaac Moe who was the owner in 1923. The house was gone by June 1930. Near this house was once the Commons of Newtown. This place was once General Moore's headquarters. It is questionably stated that the house was erected about 1700 on the site of the former Wm. Stevenson house that was acquired, in 1742 by Richard Betts. Jonathan Randel was an
occupant in 1852.
1922
Views 1 and 2
Views 3&:4rJan. 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
